			<item>
				<title>A problem on magnetism</title>
				<link>http://localhost:1313/posts/magnetism/</link>
				<pubDate>Mon, 09 Jun 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/magnetism/</guid>
				<description>&lt;p&gt;This was a problem in my final exam for the Classical Mechanics course imparted by the wonderful Kaden Hazzard. I will&#xA;attempt to describe its solution (thank you Kaden for the exam and solution manual on part &lt;em&gt;b&lt;/em&gt;!)&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;statement&#34;&gt;Statement&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Symmetries are useful for constructing Lagrangians (for an example see, my post on &lt;a href=&#34;../mean-field/&#34;&gt;mean field&lt;/a&gt;). The&#xA;Lagrangian for this system is&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;[&#xA;\mathcal{L}=i\sum_a w^*_a\partial_t w_a - c^2\sum_j\partial_j \vec{n}\cdot\partial_j\vec{n},&#xA;]&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;where (\partial_j\equiv\partial/\partial x_j), and (w(\vec{x}, t)) is a two-component field, which is nothing new if you&amp;rsquo;ve done any field theory in classical mechanics (Stone&amp;rsquo;s book on mathematical methods &lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:1&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:1&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; is a good reference for this). The first term represents the kinetic energy and the last term is clearly potential energy.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
			</item>
			<item>
				<title>Mean field theory</title>
				<link>http://localhost:1313/posts/mean-field/</link>
				<pubDate>Wed, 09 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/mean-field/</guid>
				<description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;landau-ginzburg-theory&#34;&gt;Landau-Ginzburg theory&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Essentiaylly, one expands the free energy functional $F[m]$ in $m$ and its&#xA;gradients while satisfying the proposed symmetries. The coarse-grained extension&#xA;to the Ising Hamiltonian is given by a &lt;em&gt;Landau-Ginzburg&lt;/em&gt; Hamiltonian&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;$$&#xA;H[m] = \int d\vec{r}\left[ \frac{a}{2}m^2 + bm^4 + \frac{K}{2} (\nabla m)^2 +\dots\right]&#xA;$$&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This has profound consequences in the statistical theory of fields (using&#xA;saddle-point approximations to recover Landau&amp;rsquo;s theory),&#xA;but I won&amp;rsquo;t discuss this here (see &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/statistical-physics-of-fields/06F49D11030FB3108683F413269DE945&#34;&gt;Kardar&amp;rsquo;s book&lt;/a&gt;).&#xA;Here, $m(\vec{x})$ can be interpreted to be order-parameters, but in essence&#xA;are random fields, i.e. a field with a Boltzmann weight.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
			</item>
			<item>
				<title>My research (for my parents)</title>
				<link>http://localhost:1313/extra/research/</link>
				<pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<guid>http://localhost:1313/extra/research/</guid>
				<description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;panorama&#34;&gt;Panorama&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Muchas de las propiedades magnéticas y electrónicas de los materiales son explicadas por los electrones. El descubrimiento de la mecánica cuántica puso en&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Los limones vienen en distintas formas y tamaños. Cuando agarramos un limón del árbol, no nos preocupamos por saber en dónde están las semillas, pero sí en la forma (y el color) del limón.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;../research/lemon.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;lemon&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Los orbitales atómicos son como los limones, y los electrones sus semillas. Cuentan con formas un poco más extrañas, pero al mirar detenidamente observamos que tienen mayor simetría que aquella de un limón natural. Estos orbitales originalmente fueron concebidos para el átomo de hidrógeno, y heredan un poco de la simetría rotacional del potencial de Coulomb.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
			</item>
			<item>
				<title>Rice (Water)</title>
				<link>http://localhost:1313/photos/rice_water/</link>
				<pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<guid>http://localhost:1313/photos/rice_water/</guid>
				<description>&lt;center&gt;&#xA;&lt;figure style=&#34;margin-bottom: 3rem;&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;./brockmann3.JPG&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;img src=&#34;./brockmann3.JPG&#34;&#xA;         style=&#34;width: 600px; height: auto; object-fit: contain;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;  &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/center&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;center&gt;&#xA;&lt;figure style=&#34;margin-bottom: 3rem;&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;./brockmann2.JPG&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;img src=&#34;./brockmann2.JPG&#34;&#xA;         style=&#34;width: 600px; height: auto; object-fit: contain;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;  &lt;figcaption&gt;Brockmann hall for physics&lt;/figcaption&gt;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/center&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;center&gt;&#xA;&lt;figure style=&#34;margin-bottom: 3rem;&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;./coarse_graining_b.jpg&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;img src=&#34;./coarse_graining_b.jpg&#34;&#xA;         style=&#34;width: 600px; height: auto; object-fit: contain;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;  &lt;figcaption&gt;Image (b) is a &amp;#34;coarse grained&amp;#34; version of (a), where small fluctuations are washed out (an average behaviour emerges, similar to mean-field).&lt;/figcaption&gt;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/center&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;center&gt;&#xA;&lt;figure style=&#34;margin-bottom: 3rem;&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;./coarse_graining_a.jpg&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;img src=&#34;./coarse_graining_a.jpg&#34;&#xA;         style=&#34;width: 600px; height: auto; object-fit: contain;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;  &lt;figcaption&gt;When scaled, image (b) fits right in to image (a).&lt;/figcaption&gt;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/center&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;center&gt;&#xA;&lt;figure style=&#34;margin-bottom: 3rem;&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;./escher1.1.JPG&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;img src=&#34;./escher1.1.JPG&#34;&#xA;         style=&#34;width: 600px; height: auto; object-fit: contain;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;  &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/center&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;center&gt;&#xA;&lt;figure style=&#34;margin-bottom: 3rem;&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a href=&#34;./escher2.JPG&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;img src=&#34;./escher2.JPG&#34;&#xA;         style=&#34;width: 600px; height: auto; object-fit: contain;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;  &lt;figcaption&gt;Houston can be very rainy&lt;/figcaption&gt;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/center&gt;</description>
